  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) are people who are forced to flee their homes due to armed conflict, generalized violence, violations of human rights, natural or human-made disasters, but who remain within their own country.28 million new people became internally displaced by conflict and disasters worldwide in the course of 2018. 10.8 million of these were displaced by violence and conflict, and 17.2 million by natural disaster. In total, there are over 41.3 million IDPs worldwide, the highest number ever recorded.The top three countries with the largest internally displaced populations due to conflict and violence in 2018 were Ethiopia, the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) and Syria. The top three countries with the largest number of IDPs due to disasters in 2018 were Myanmar, Kenya and Afghanistan. An overlap of conflict and disasters repeatedly displaced people in Afghanistan, Nigeria, Somalia and other countries.</narrative>
